# 05 - Props in React (Component Inputs)

---

# 1. What are Props?

Props (short for "properties") are used to pass data from one component to another.

Props are:
- Read-only
- Passed from parent to child
- Used to make components reusable

Think of props like function parameters.

---

# 2. Passing Data via Props (Basic Example)

## Step 1: Create Child Component

Create `User.jsx`

```jsx
function User(props) {
  return <h2>Hello {props.name}</h2>;
}

export default User;
````

---

## Step 2: Pass Props from Parent

In `App.jsx`

```jsx
import User from "./User";

function App() {
  return (
    <div>
      <User name="Varun" />
      <User name="Rahul" />
    </div>
  );
}

export default App;
```

Output:
Hello Varun
Hello Rahul

Each component receives different data.

---

# 3. Passing Multiple Props

```jsx
function User(props) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>Name: {props.name}</h2>
      <p>Role: {props.role}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

Usage:

```jsx
<User name="Varun" role="Trainer" />
```

---

# 4. Destructuring Props (Cleaner Way)

Instead of writing:

```jsx
function User(props) {
  return <h2>{props.name}</h2>;
}
```

Use destructuring:

```jsx
function User({ name, role }) {
  return (
    <div>
      <h2>{name}</h2>
      <p>{role}</p>
    </div>
  );
}
```

This makes code cleaner and more readable.

---

# 5. Default Props

Default props provide fallback values if no prop is passed.

## Method 1: Default Parameters (Recommended)

```jsx
function User({ name = "Guest" }) {
  return <h2>Hello {name}</h2>;
}
```

If no name is passed:

```jsx
<User />
```

Output:
Hello Guest

---

## Method 2: Using defaultProps (Older Method)

```jsx
User.defaultProps = {
  name: "Guest"
};
```

Note: Default parameters are preferred in modern React.

---

# 6. Passing Functions as Props

Props can also pass functions.

This allows child components to communicate with parent components.

---

## Step 1: Parent Component

```jsx
function App() {
  function handleClick() {
    alert("Button Clicked!");
  }

  return <Button onClick={handleClick} />;
}
```

---

## Step 2: Child Component

```jsx
function Button({ onClick }) {
  return <button onClick={onClick}>Click Me</button>;
}

export default Button;
```

This is called "lifting state up".

---

# 7. Passing Data Back to Parent

Example:

## Parent

```jsx
function App() {
  function receiveData(data) {
    console.log(data);
  }

  return <Child sendData={receiveData} />;
}
```

## Child

```jsx
function Child({ sendData }) {
  return (
    <button onClick={() => sendData("Hello Parent")}>
      Send Data
    </button>
  );
}
```

Now child sends data to parent.

---

# 8. Children Props

React provides a special prop called `children`.

It represents whatever is placed between component tags.

---

## Example

```jsx
function Card({ children }) {
  return (
    <div style={{ border: "1px solid black", padding: "10px" }}>
      {children}
    </div>
  );
}
```

Usage:

```jsx
<Card>
  <h2>Title</h2>
  <p>This is inside card.</p>
</Card>
```

Everything inside `<Card>` becomes `children`.

---

# 9. Passing Objects as Props

```jsx
function User({ user }) {
  return <h2>{user.name}</h2>;
}
```

Usage:

```jsx
const userData = { name: "Varun", age: 25 };

<User user={userData} />
```

---

# 10. Passing Arrays as Props

```jsx
function List({ items }) {
  return (
    <ul>
      {items.map((item, index) => (
        <li key={index}>{item}</li>
      ))}
    </ul>
  );
}
```

Usage:

```jsx
<List items={["React", "Node", "Django"]} />
```

---

# 11. Important Props Rules

1. Props are read-only.
2. Props flow from parent to child.
3. Never modify props directly.
4. Use destructuring for cleaner code.
5. Use keys when passing lists.

---

# 12. Props vs State

| Props                     | State                       |
| ------------------------- | --------------------------- |
| Passed from parent        | Managed inside component    |
| Read-only                 | Can change                  |
| Makes components reusable | Controls component behavior |

